					<div id=3D"mw-content-text" class=3D"mw-body-content"><div class=3D"mw=
-content-ltr mw-parser-output" lang=3D"en" dir=3D"ltr"><div class=3D"shortd=
escription nomobile noexcerpt noprint searchaux" style=3D"display:none">Sta=
tistical hypothesis test</div>
<div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">Not to be co=
nfused with <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wilcoxon_rank-sum_test=
" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Wilcoxon rank-sum test">Wilcoxon rank-sum =
test</a>.</div>
<p>The <b>Wilcoxon signed-rank test</b> is a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedi=
a.org/wiki/Non-parametric_statistics" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Non-pa=
rametric statistics">non-parametric</a> <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org=
/wiki/Rank_test" title=3D"Rank test">rank test</a> for <a href=3D"https://e=
n.wikipedia.org/wiki/Statistical_hypothesis_testing" class=3D"mw-redirect" =
title=3D"Statistical hypothesis testing">statistical hypothesis testing</a>=
 used either to test the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Location_=
parameter" title=3D"Location parameter">location</a> of a population based =
on a sample of data, or to compare the locations of two populations using t=
wo matched samples.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Conover_1-0" class=3D"reference"><a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wilcoxon_signed-rank_test#cite_note-C=
onover-1"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>1<span class=3D"cite-bracket=
">]</span></a></sup> The one-sample version serves a purpose similar to tha=
t of the one-sample <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Student%27s_t-=
test" title=3D"Student's t-test">Student's <i>t</i>-test</a>.<sup id=3D"cit=
e_ref-2" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wilco=
xon_signed-rank_test#cite_note-2"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>2<sp=
an class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> For two matched samples, it is=
 a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Paired_difference_test" title=
=3D"Paired difference test">paired difference test</a> like the paired Stud=
ent's <i>t</i>-test (also known as the "<i>t</i>-test for matched pairs" or=
 "<i>t</i>-test for dependent samples"). The Wilcoxon test is a good altern=
ative to the  <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/T-test" class=3D"mw-=
redirect" title=3D"T-test">t-test</a> when the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipe=
dia.org/wiki/Normal_distribution" title=3D"Normal distribution">normal dist=
ribution</a> of the differences between paired individuals cannot be assume=
d. Instead, it assumes a weaker hypothesis that the distribution of this di=
fference   is symmetric  around a central value  and it aims to test whethe=
r this center value differs significantly from zero. The Wilcoxon test is a=
 more powerful alternative to the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/=
Sign_test" title=3D"Sign test">sign test</a> because it considers the magni=
tude of the differences, but it requires this moderately strong assumption =
of symmetry.
</p>
<meta property=3D"mw:PageProp/toc">
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"History">History</h2><span =
class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DWilcoxon_signed-rank_t=
est&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D1" title=3D"Edit section: History"><spa=
n>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></di=
v>
<p>The test is named after <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Frank_W=
ilcoxon" title=3D"Frank Wilcoxon">Frank Wilcoxon</a> (1892=E2=80=931965) wh=
o, in a single paper, proposed both it and the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipe=
dia.org/wiki/Mann-Whitney-Wilcoxon_test" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Man=
n-Whitney-Wilcoxon test">rank-sum test</a> for two independent samples.<sup=
 id=3D"cite_ref-Wilcoxon_3-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wik=
ipedia.org/wiki/Wilcoxon_signed-rank_test#cite_note-Wilcoxon-3"><span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>3<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> =
The test was popularized by <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sidney=
_Siegel" title=3D"Sidney Siegel">Sidney Siegel</a> (1956) in his influentia=
l textbook on non-parametric statistics.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Siegel_4-0" cla=
ss=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wilcoxon_signed-r=
ank_test#cite_note-Siegel-4"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>4<span cl=
ass=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> Siegel used the symbol <i>T</i> for=
 the test statistic, and consequently, the test is sometimes referred to as=
 the <b>Wilcoxon <i>T</i>-test</b>.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Test_procedure">Test proced=
ure</h2><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracke=
t">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DWilcoxon=
_signed-rank_test&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D2" title=3D"Edit section:=
 Test procedure"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket=
">]</span></span></div>
<p>There are two variants of the signed-rank test. From a theoretical point=
 of view, the one-sample test is more fundamental because the paired sample=
 test is performed by converting the data to the situation of the one-sampl=
e test. However, most practical applications of the signed-rank test arise =
from paired data.
</p><p>For a paired sample test, the data consists of a sample <span class=
