ket">]</span></span></div>
<p>The one-sample Wilcoxon signed-rank test can be used to test whether dat=
a comes from a symmetric population with a specified center (which correspo=
nds to <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Median" title=3D"Median">me=
dian</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mean" title=3D"Mean">mea=
n</a> and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pseudomedian" title=3D"P=
seudomedian">pseudomedian</a>).<sup id=3D"cite_ref-11" class=3D"reference">=
<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wilcoxon_signed-rank_test#cite_not=
e-11"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>11<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]=
</span></a></sup> If the population center is known, then it can be used to=
 test whether data is symmetric about its center.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Hettma=
nsperger_12-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki=
/Wilcoxon_signed-rank_test#cite_note-Hettmansperger-12"><span class=3D"cite=
-bracket">[</span>12<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>To explain the null and alternative hypotheses formally, assume that=
 the data consists of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Independent_=
and_identically_distributed_random_variables" title=3D"Independent and iden=
tically distributed random variables">independent and identically distribut=
ed</a> samples from a distribution <span class=3D"mwe-math-element mwe-math=
-element-inline"><span class=3D"mwe-math-mathml-inline mwe-math-mathml-a11y=
" style=3D"display: none;"><math xmlns=3D"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathM=
