<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Effect_size">Effect size</h=
2><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</=
span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DWilcoxon_signe=
d-rank_test&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D12" title=3D"Edit section: Effe=
ct size"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</spa=
n></span></div>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1320445320"><div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">=
Main article: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mann%E2%80%93Whitney=
_U_test#Rank-biserial_correlation" title=3D"Mann=E2=80=93Whitney U test">Ma=
nn=E2=80=93Whitney_U_test =C2=A7&nbsp;Rank-biserial_correlation</a></div>
<p>To compute an <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Effect_size" titl=
e=3D"Effect size">effect size</a> for the signed-rank test, one can use the=
 <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mann%E2%80%93Whitney_U_test#Rank-=
biserial_correlation" title=3D"Mann=E2=80=93Whitney U test">rank-biserial c=
orrelation</a>.
</p><p>If the test statistic <i>T</i> is reported, the rank correlation r i=
s equal to the test statistic <i>T</i> divided by the total rank sum <i>S</=
i>, or&nbsp;<i>r</i>&nbsp;=3D&nbsp;<i>T</i>/<i>S</i>.
<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Kerby2014_53-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://=
en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wilcoxon_signed-rank_test#cite_note-Kerby2014-53"><sp=
an class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>53<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></=
a></sup> Using the above example, the test statistic is <i>T</i> =3D 9. The=
 sample size of 9 has a total rank sum of <i>S</i> =3D (1 + 2 + 3 + 4 + 5 +=
 6 + 7 + 8 + 9) =3D 45. Hence, the rank correlation is 9/45, so <i>r</i> =
=3D 0.20.
</p><p>If the test statistic <i>T</i> is reported, an equivalent way to com=
pute the rank correlation is with the difference in proportion between the =
two rank sums, which is the Kerby (2014) simple difference formula.<sup id=
=3D"cite_ref-Kerby2014_53-1" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wiki=
pedia.org/wiki/Wilcoxon_signed-rank_test#cite_note-Kerby2014-53"><span clas=
s=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>53<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup=
> To continue with the current example, the sample size is 9, so the total =
rank sum is 45. <i>T</i> is the smaller of the two rank sums, so <i>T</i> i=
s 3 + 4 + 5 + 6 =3D 18. From this information alone, the remaining rank sum=
 can be computed, because it is the total sum <i>S</i> minus <i>T</i>, or i=
n this case 45 =E2=88=92 18 =3D 27. Next, the two rank-sum proportions are =
27/45 =3D 60% and 18/45 =3D 40%. Finally, the rank correlation is the diffe=
rence between the two proportions (.60 minus .40), hence <i>r</i> =3D .20.
</p>
